Get data and compute values needed

load(file=file.path("Rdata","workdata.RData"))
workdata %<>%
  mutate(Hofer_ant_u=Hofer_u/Tot_u,
         Hofer_ant_m=Hofer_m/Tot_m) 
workdata %>% select(Hofer_u,Hofer_m,Tot_u,Tot_m) %>%
  colSums() -> toterg
shiftneeded <- ceiling((toterg[3]+toterg[4])/2-(toterg[1]+toterg[2]))
hofer_behind <- (toterg[3]+toterg[4]) - 2 * (toterg[1]+toterg[2])
workdata %>%
  select(incrim11,Tot_m,Hofer_m,Tot_u,Hofer_u) %>%
   group_by(incrim11) %>%
  summarise_each("sum") ->
  sums11
tot11m <- sums11[[1,2]]
hofer11m <- sums11[[1,3]]
hofer11u <- sums11[[1,5]]
hoferneeds11 <- (hofer11m + shiftneeded)

Computing probabilities for changing election outcome in different scenarios

Linear model with 11 districts removed

workdata %>% filter(!(incrim11 == "beanst.")) %>%
  ntbt_lm(Hofer_m ~ Hofer_u - 1,weights=1/Tot_m) ->
  model11

Data frame for prediction sum of 11 districts

preddf11 <- data.frame(Hofer_u=hofer11u,Tot_m=tot11m)

Auxiliary function

predict.lm computes prediction intervals for given confidence levels. Our problem is the other way round, we compute the probability od the prediction exceeding a given target value.

To do this, we compute a prediction interval for 95% level using the classical prediction estimator for linear models build into R (which uses a rescaled t-disribution), extract the value by which the t-distribution for this prediction has been rescaled, and use this scale value to compute the probability for a given prediction interval width.

find_prob_pred_geq <- function(model,preddf,targetval){
  pred <- predict.lm(model,preddf,interval="prediction",weights=~1/Tot_m,level=0.95)
  predscale <- (pred[1]-pred[2])/qt(0.975,df.residual(model))
  res <- 1-pt((targetval-pred[1])/predscale,df.residual(model))
  names(res) <- NULL
  res
}

Probability for sum of 11 districts changing election outcome, model without 11 districts

myprob <- find_prob_pred_geq(model11,preddf11,hoferneeds11)  
myprob %>% cat()
1.322065e-10
printfixed <- function(x)sprintf("%.0f",x)

We can check that the the probability really gives the target value as limit of the confidence interval.

Hofer lost by 3.086310^{4}, and he has 34479 votes in the contaminated districts. So he needs 15432 more mail votes there, making for a total of 49911 mail votes in the contaminated districts.

Let us check the corresponding prediction confidence interval with probability 0.999999999736

predict(model11,preddf11,interval="prediction",weights=~1/Tot_m, level=1-2*myprob)
       fit      lwr   upr
1 33401.16 16891.33 49911
